This boy realizes that it is wrong to publicize obscene photographs, photographs of naked persons or photographs of crimes, or to write humiliating or rough comments.
Jorge says he knows all 35 friends he's got on FB and nine favorites on Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
Among them is a mother who has a name and a password of one of the accounts.
"I found an account on Twitter so that I can express my views and write interesting contributions.
I don't know if anyone answers me, I'm just giving them there," he adds.
"Social networks are funny, I can talk to relatives who are far or fast to communicate with friends," he says.
Without hesitation, he says he would never accept a request from an unknown person.
He wouldn't even care if someone recommended someone stranger to him.
The case of the 14 - year - old José is different.
This teenager owns Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask accounts and in the last mentioned network admits that he doesn't know 20 people from his list of friends.
"I'm not afraid of it because we have something in common, like music," he says.
According to this boy, none of them wanted a address or a phone number after him.
"If they insisted on me or demanded it from me, I will simply remove them from my account," he admits.
José signed up on Ask after he read the Twitter recommendations.
This boy is not an alien experience with what it's called cyberbullying today.
"Known friends were blackmailed on social networks.
They threatened him and asked for money.
He never knew who it was," he confirmed.
According to José, the victim didn't sign up on the account.
"Only activated private regime."
Then explains the series of steps how to set the account safely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would have published photos known in unpleasant or embarrassing situations.
"Of course I would have done it if someone was disturbing me or just wishing.
Even though I know it's cyberbullying," he says.
Key Questions
Marielos Porras, English teacher and a graduate in the field of education and teaching, believes that children and teenagers in social networks need to understand that the main objective of these networks is to inform them.
