It explains that it is a complicated theme, "because we ask them to recognize what is appropriate to spread, publicize and say, and what not, when they are not mature."
Also, to be - about the environment - reasonable, at the time what they desire most is to be favorite, to have thousands of friends and not to think about the consequences," he adds.
According to this specialist, the most effective way to show children and adolescents what is privacy, asking questions that make them think.
"Tell them not to do anything, it doesn't work," he adds.
Furthermore, Marrielos Porras emphasizes some of the options: There are things you wouldn't tell a stranger, so why are you doing this online?
Or: Would you like someone to publish your picture as you published a friend?
Do you know what the others say about you?
When you mark people on the photos of celebration, did you ask these people for permission?
And another: do everyone need to know what you're doing all the time?
The next point is to realize that they must be acting in the Internet as outside.
They're the same rules.
"A person is administered outside the Internet with respect, moral and other principles and should be the same on social networks," he says.
Oversight
Estuardo Guarddia, university professor, teacher at first degree, and educational adviser explains that it is necessary that children are carefully read the rules of social networks.
"If he understands every indication, they have a good basis to talk to their children about the consequences that the establishment of an account on the Internet can have.
